122ee992-3ae9-4781-ac1d-daf3361b01ab	even-gopis-get-the-blues	Even Gopis Get the Blues	The life of a yogi is one of complete dedication to the attainment of the full development of the human spiritual potential. This goal requires ceaseless effort; mindfulness; Self-enquiry; refinement of thought, speech and action; sublimation of impulses and cessation of old sanskaras.	text	gyani	0	\N	\N	The life of a yogi is one of complete dedication to the attainment of the full development of the human spiritual potential. This goal requires ceaseless effort; mindfulness; Self-enquiry; refinement of thought, speech and action; sublimation of impulses and cessation of old sanskaras.The yogic life is one of purity of mind and heart, nobility and generosity of spirit, egoless action, and disciplined patterns of relationship, in order to remain untouched by maya, the illusion of body-identification that produces all forms of suffering.The yogi must be both a gyani and a bhakta—a Self-reflective cognitive atmanologist and metaphysicist and simultaneously a devotee mad with the ecstasy of divine love.By flying with the aid of these two wings, one stabilizes one’s flight to the celestial realms of Light, until the soul dissolves entirely into the Absolute.On the phenomenal plane, life is lived in the paradoxical unity of duality and nonduality. This is what the Vaishnav saints mean by being a gopi—literally, a cowgirl, a dedicated keeper of the sacred cow, symbol of the divine giver of the milk of human kindness and the primal sound of om. There are, of course, both gopes and gopis, cowherds in male and female forms, who milk the Goddess of Love and share the cream of Her creation, the nectar of sweetest grace and joy.The gope or gopi is most of all an enraptured lover of Krishna, an incarnation of God; the gopi is a lover who is also part of the same beloved avataric nonduality-within-duality. This is expressed by the subtle concept of achintya bhedabheda. This means that opposite realities are nested within one another: nonduality within duality, and vice versa; samsara within nirvana, and vice versa; time within eternity, and vice versa; and on and on, with every metaphysical set of binaries.The gopi sees the Supreme everywhere, as the intelligent life force pervading every being, every appearance, every moment, including the consciousness that is the perceiver thereof. The passion for the formless One shining through the myriad forms seemingly objectively separate, yet all pointing to the Supreme Self that emanates and animates this play of self-luminous consciousness, sustains the gopi/yogi in her joyous constancy of pure sublime Presence.But occasionally, maya may break through and disturb even an adept gopi’s peace of mind. In fact, maya is nested within lila, and lila within maya. There is recognition of all this as the perfect play of divine goodness. But this perception may oscillate with egoic frustration at the resistances of the Real to achieving the harmony of heavenly flow. The density of the tamasic world seemingly defies the will of heaven.The ego wants to surrender its lower impulses, and to see the divine, the shining subtle Light, in everyone. But at times it may see only a narcissistic ego, or only a threat to one’s own narcissistic equilibrium. At times, the gopi may want to go pee on the Other, feeling envy for the imagined superiority of another’s beauty or goodness or strength or intelligence. Or lustful desire may raise its ugly head. Or there may be momentary hatred of someone who has rebuffed one’s advances or offers of friendship.All this is enough to give any self-respecting gopi a case of the blues. Sometimes, one may have to sing the blues literally. At other times, one may have to write sad poetry or keep a diary of such egoic excreta, in order not to contaminate one’s interpersonal relationships. But slogging through the mud of maya is an inherent part of the great journey to ego transcendence.From the infantile bawling and sulking of the blues, a gopi who is intent on growing through the pain of loss and acceptance of impermanence forms the blue note into jazz; a gopi who is intent on transforming the ego into a soulful structure of integrity, strength, maturity, empowerment, and vision, will use the pain of abandonment and loneliness, the anxiety of separation, the terror of life lived alone in a world suddenly shredded into an abyss of despair, to riff a musical sculpture of ascending octaves of supreme desire for Liberation; from being bereft in a space without reference points, falling through nothingness, groundless, meaningless, pointlessly alive…the gopi gathers the strength of faith to go through ego death. The music of the spheres is heard on the akashic airwaves.The long, dark night of the soul cannot be evaded. But now the angels sing in the moonlight of the night sea journey. And while the gopi listens to the primeval om sound coming from amidst the sacred cows, heard even in the darkness, a heavenly trumpet sounds in resonance; she sees the gold-blue glow of Krishna in the distance, along with primal percussions of tambourines and drums; she attunes to the sweet love song of Radha, Her voice voluptuous with absolute surrender; and then the whirling, rhythmic dance of ultimate divine devotion, opens the portal to the dimension beyond, so close, so far, so yearned for.Here the coming home gets supremely real, the whole of time is but a vanished dream, as the kirtan calls, the yearning of the heart responds, and Krishna is revealed—as I. The heart pulls presence deeper inward now, it recognizes all phenomena as mere projections of the Self, guideposts on the path to silence. And the goal is reached. All illusion falls away into the stillness, the music absolute, sat chit ananda…the last swaha!Yes, even gopis get the blues. But the blues never get the gopis. They are always riding the crest of the rising wave, detached from both suffering and joy, knowing the passionate union of Radha-Krishna is the only Real, that bliss eternal is our home, no matter what we may be feeling in a momentary passage through a wisp of maya fog.When gopis get the blues, they turn it into music that shakes the foundations of the ego’s world. They may hit bottom, but only to spring back up, all the way to the highest realm of Anuttara. When gopis get the blues, their song of desire for reunion with the One opens even the heart of Shiva, Who carries them to the holy mountain, Arunachala. Shiva takes the poison of their suffering away, and swallows it. So even Shiva gets the blues, at least in His throat. That is God’s service, when He works through a form.Though even gopis get the blues, as we approach the deep blue sea of Love and the infinite blue sky of Mind, beyond the reach of maya’s pull, only the serenity and coolness of the royal blue of the true third eye remains. The Self dissolves all pain. Sat Yuga will dawn once more, and even Krishna’s tone seems brighter now—now that the gopis blew away their blues.Namaste,Shunyamurti\nTopics covered in this teaching:\nOvercoming Obstacles	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2020/05/1-2.jpg	\N	2019-07-01 09:29:34	essay	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.375087	2025-10-28 15:31:24.375087	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
