36e3efb5-3ca6-45bb-ba37-0c176e499043	the-meaning-of-self-realization	The Meaning of Self-Realization	The difficulty in explaining the meaning of Self-realization is that the mind tends to understand everything from within the paradigm of subject-object duality, and that is the very obstacle to the Self-realization we wish to achieve.	text	gyani	0	\N	\N	The difficulty in explaining the meaning of Self-realization is that the mind tends to understand everything from within the paradigm of subject-object duality, and that is the very obstacle to the Self-realization we wish to achieve.That dualistic paradigm, which is illusory, structures language itself, so the very categories of thought by which we attempt to understand ourselves, prevent understanding from occurring. This is the double bind on the symbolic level.The more intelligent we become in terms of being able to manipulate symbolic forms, the more alienated we become from the Real that lies beyond the realm of symbols. And so we can say that Self-realization is a matter of surrender of the power of symbolic manipulation, investigation, and articulation to the higher power of Presence.Once we enter into the realm of symbols, we have sacrificed our Presence, the mind dwells in a secondary realm that orbits around Presence, much as a satellite orbits around the earth, a realm that represents the Presence, but is not that.“The word murders the thing,” as Hegel once said. And so we enter into this plane where we think we understand everything, but in fact we truly touch nothing. We have alienated ourselves from the Essence of Being, in order to understand it, to grasp it conceptually, but the conceptual understanding has removed us from the Heart, which is the only true understanding.And so, while we do not want to lose our symbolic capacity, we need not sacrifice our Being. But only by recognizing the higher power of Presence can the lower power of symbolic mapping become transformed into an instrument of the Self.Because the ego is identified with this power of symbolic articulation (because it is both a weapon and a tool, which is very useful for egoic purposes on the phenomenal plane), the ego strives to appropriate all symbolic maps to use for its own purposes. This makes the conceptual grids useless as means of reaching our Being.But once we have centered ourselves in our Being, we can use those tools of symbolic knowledge for the purpose of transforming the ego structure itself. To accomplish this, however, we must be dis-identified from the ego. But if we are identified with that tool, if we think of ourselves as symbolic entities, then we will be possessed by the egoic logic, which is always obsessed with gaining power over others.And the very addiction to that illusory power, the phenomenal power, rather than the surrender to the real power, the noumenal power of Supreme Being, seduces us into further illusion. So the spiritual battle revolves around the courage and truthfulness required not to abuse the illusory power that symbolic manipulation gives us, while taking us away from the Heart, our true Self.And so we can measure our progress in the spiritual realm, by the degree of surrender of the discursive intellectual mind that wants to use sophisticated forms of thought for its own territorial purposes, rather than to effect surrender to the Supreme Presence that is beyond thought.Paradoxically, the more that the discursive mind surrenders to the Heart, which is the Divine Presence, the more intelligence there will be at the symbolic level, because the symbolizing egoic mind is taken in by its very sense of intelligence and it falls for the rationalizations of the “I of the statement,” the superficial false self, and considers them valid . And so, the mind, for all its sophistication, becomes gullible and naïve. It foolishly believes the words that it hears coming from its own mouth or mind, and it looses touch with who is speaking. We must discern not only the words that are coming out of our mouths, but the level of subjectivity that is enunciating those words.It is when we recognize the “I of the enunciation” behind the words as a hidden object within, that we can begin to listen from an even deeper place, in a state of pure awareness that is not egoic. Once we awaken to the Self that is behind the enunciating ego, the third ear that is listening, and that is within the Real Self, we can begin to see the Real in everyone. Then the illusory paradigms of discourse will no longer fool us into believing in unrealities.But the primary unreality that we must overcome is the unreality of the ego, the self-identification with a linguistically centered program rooted in an body image. The surrender to pure Presence that is beyond language enables us to touch into the power of Being, which is known as love.The more we sit in meditation, with an active but silent awareness, we have not become mind-less but mind-ful. We have awakened the greater mind, the mind of silence that has direct intuition of the Real. It does not have to think about the Real, because it is That.The more that we are in that state, the more peaceful, serene we feel, the more unshakeable we are, the less prone to any kind of emotional rollercoaster or oscillation, the more we are free from depression, anxiety, and all the other pathologies that the egoic discursive mind is subject to.The ego mind lacks true Being, it is identified with appearances and constructs, and therefore is prone to believing in whatever delusional thoughts, images, and charged emotional scenarios arise in it. The egoic mind can be taken over, it can be possessed, whereas pure Presence can never be possessed by any lesser power, because it is at one with the ultimate reality.Presence is the Real that gave birth to the ego, sustains it, and must now refine it, purify it, and dissolve it back into the Supreme Self from which all emerged. The spiritual journey begins when one is bored with the ego, with its sufferings, and with all of the houses of cards that it can create.Consciousness understands the uses of egoic capacities, but it also understands their limitations, and now it wants something more, there is a hunger for the Absolute, for a meaning that transcends meaning itself, that transcends the limited paradigms that are based upon an organismic-centered reality, and wants to know the higher reality of the cosmos, the ultimate reality that was there before there was a cosmos, and that ultimate Real is not somewhere else, it is here and now.When consciousness is willing to let go of its attachment to mentally grasping the world, it realizes that it is in fact one with the source and the power that is the creative manifestation of the world, and it is the sacrifice of its worldly appearance into its Essence that is the most difficult challenge.As we proceed in the process of Self-enquiry, not through trying to understand the Self philosophically, metaphysically, but through simple Presence, the benefits of this letting-go become palpable. They give us such an exalted experience and imperience of what is true, and finally the power to overcome all of those tendencies of the mind that could not be overcome from within the ego, so that the limited identity can finally be let go of easily.At that moment, the transcendence of form into the formless takes place. In that transcendence there is also a transcendence of the duality between form and the formless, there is a recognition that the formless is form, the emptiness is all, the universe is Brahman, they are not two, they are not even one, this is the zero-point where all and nothing merge, and it is at this point that the Supreme Real is truly realized.\nTopics covered in this teaching:\nPhilosophyYoga	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2020/05/1-2.jpg	\N	2019-06-30 21:28:10	essay	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.417042	2025-10-28 15:31:24.417042	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
