43a308fb-a230-4aef-8c60-11ee4b2bc92b	the-miracle-of-consciousness	The Miracle of Consciousness	Consciousness is the great miracle. Most people take the miracle for granted. And most remain at the very surface of consciousness without ever exploring its depths; without ever wondering: “What is consciousness really capable of?”\nWe do not learn to use the gift that we are given. And in the modern age, the intelligence that has been used has focused only on the objective aspect of consciousness: it is focused only on the manipulation of what has been quaintly called “matter”, without fully understanding what it is manipulating, but being able to produce extraordinary gadgets, extraordinary means of communications, extraordinary means of altering the environment, extraordinary means of calculation.	videoandaudio	gyani	0	\N	\N	\N	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2019/07/The-Miracle-of-Consciousness.png	\N	2019-07-01 20:36:58	video_teaching	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.306227	2025-10-28 15:31:24.306227	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
1af43139-d3d0-4471-a191-89dea732088f	false-consciousness-then-and-now	False Consciousness: Then and Now	In the 19th century, Western civilization discovered that it was living in false consciousness, and we begin to have the appearance of literary stories such as Jekyll and Hyde and The Portrait of Dorian Gray and other literary productions that came out of the Romantic movement that portrayed this split consciousness and came with the recognition that we were not masters over our own motivations, over our own bodies, over our own understanding of reality, and that there were levels of consciousness—that we had no access to—that were running our lives.	videoandaudio	gyani	0	\N	\N	\N	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2019/07/False-Consciousness-Then-and-Now.png	\N	2019-07-01 20:35:02	video_teaching	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.306974	2025-10-28 15:31:24.306974	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
d8697d6b-878d-4077-998b-7c32b942ac50	el-hombre-propone-dios-dispone	“El Hombre Propone, Dios Dispone”	The old cliché “El hombre propone y Dios dispone” [“Man proposes, God disposes”] is an eternal truth. No matter how much effort we make to achieve anything, especially in the spiritual field, success is owed to the grace of God, not to human effort. And the outcome of whatever we do, no matter how well planned, can never be guaranteed. But only the Will of God will determine the destiny of our actions and our existence..	videoandaudio	gyani	0	\N	\N	\N	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2019/07/EL-HOMBRE-PROPONE-.png	\N	2019-07-01 20:32:16	video_teaching	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.307729	2025-10-28 15:31:24.307729	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
8bcf3de5-8cf6-47ed-882b-6635ba0a2ebb	melting-into-the-flame-of-being	Melting Into the Flame of Being	Meditation is when no one does nothing. But to get to the point of realizing you are no one requires absolute focus on the consciousness that is seeking to discover its own essence and discovers only emptiness. But in that discovery, the conditions of existence are altered through the slowing down of metabolic processes and of thought processes that in turn slow down time and enable a deepening of awareness to attain the source of the very will to know the self and to melt back into that original Eternal Self..	videoandaudio	gyani	0	\N	\N	\N	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2019/07/Melting-Into-the-Flame-of-Being.png	\N	2019-07-01 20:29:20	video_teaching	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.30903	2025-10-28 15:31:24.30903	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
d9667781-4702-4bcb-927c-8d0325b717ca	the-fall-of-greatness	The Fall of Greatness	The time of the ego is over. This is a historic reality. There are no more great egos.Once upon a time in Kali Yuga, the goal of life was to become a great man or a great woman, and there was even a theory that the great man made history. There are no longer great men or great women. There are no longer great artists. There are no longer great thinkers. There are no longer great saints or sages..	videoandaudio	gyani	0	\N	\N	\N	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2019/07/The-Fall-of-Greatness.png	\N	2019-07-01 20:26:41	video_teaching	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.311147	2025-10-28 15:31:24.311147	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
21fce514-e717-4566-879c-f4f626cac836	the-journey-beyond-meaning	The Journey Beyond Meaning	The Real is blissful because it is formless and other-less and because it is beyond meaning and beyond any sense of “I”, and those are the criteria of purity of consciousness that has been decontaminated of duality. For the ego consciousness—for that very low level of awareness and intelligence that inhabits a phantasmatic realm of multiplicity—there cannot be bliss, but the ego functions in terms of its relationship between jouissance and meaning.	videoandaudio	gyani	0	\N	\N	\N	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2019/07/The-Journey-Beyond-Meaning.png	\N	2019-07-01 20:24:55	video_teaching	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.313032	2025-10-28 15:31:24.313032	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
25e02079-d3fa-4808-b061-586adc16799e	meditation-is-de-reification	Meditation is De-Reification	Reification comes from the Latin word res, which means “thing”. The modern age is characterized and often identified with the work of Rene Descartes in the 1600s, who began his meditations with the understanding that the soul, the consciousness, is res cogitans, a thinking thing. As soon as that presupposition was made of being a thing, then there was no way out of the conceptualization of a world of things and of thing-hood as the basic principle of reality.	videoandaudio	gyani	0	\N	\N	\N	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2019/07/Meditation-is-De-Reification.png	\N	2019-07-01 20:22:21	video_teaching	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.314546	2025-10-28 15:31:24.314546	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
d4054b40-ad9a-4186-840f-6135f6d5b9ea	no-artificial-ingredients	No Artificial Ingredients	A Sat Yogi is consciousness without artificial ingredients. It is the removal of everything artificial within consciousness. That is the work of the sadhana of the Sat Yogi: to realize consciousness as it is in itself, in its purity; consciousness without any imported ingredients or without the belief that there is anywhere from which ingredients could be imported; consciousness independent of thought forms, unattached to thought forms, including thought forms that are projected as external others; and therefore consciousness without longing, without regret, without desire, without lack, but also without lack of lack; consciousness without attribute, without attachment, but also without detachment, because there is nothing to be either attached or detached to or from.	videoandaudio	gyani	0	\N	\N	\N	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2019/07/No-Artificial-Ingredients.png	\N	2019-07-01 20:17:59	video_teaching	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.315575	2025-10-28 15:31:24.315575	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
d67e9861-ef30-4fa6-b00b-8168bbdf6e0b	the-true-practice-of-sat-yoga	The True Practice of Sat Yoga	The true practice of Sat Yoga is the cessation of all mental activity while abiding in the highest center of consciousness. It is that cessation, stillness, that removes all interference patterns and all differentiation—between the attention that is abiding, and that power in which the consciousness is enveloped and there is a merging into God Consciousness—that can remain as the Truth of our Being, but can remain so only if there has been achieved prior to that, a complete purification of thought and desire, affect, body, speech and activity; because impurities at any of those levels will draw the attention back into the phenomenal plane, into body consciousness, into the illusion of maya, and any unfinished business, uncompleted, unresolved desires or fears that remain, pull the attention down from the highest center and bring one back into the form of a seeker.	videoandaudio	gyani	0	\N	\N	\N	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2019/07/The-True-Practice-of-Sat-Yoga.png	\N	2019-07-01 20:15:32	video_teaching	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.316249	2025-10-28 15:31:24.316249	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
8d09d139-705f-4dc4-8c7b-65d124a0476f	the-hustler-starring-paul-newman	The Hustler, starring Paul Newman	Why The Hustler? So many allusions to recent teachings could of course be mentioned. It is about the game of pool, which involves disappearance and death, but also growth of character and facing the deepest pain, thus becoming the Bodhisattva of Compassion.	text	gyani	0	\N	\N	Why The Hustler? So many allusions to recent teachings could of course be mentioned. It is about the game of pool, which involves disappearance and death, but also growth of character and facing the deepest pain, thus becoming the Bodhisattva of Compassion.\nWe could mention the writing on the mirror (I won’t say more, so not to spoil it) that includes the word “perverted,” and perhaps understand it in the context of the perversion that is the twisted root of every ego.We can also view the film as showing us Kali Yuga headed for a cataclysm. The film lays out the full disgusting display of the rotten core the empire of modernity. Our faces are shoved into the waste of deadened consciousness, the corruption of life in the good old USA, the barren desert of the real, where the only way to make a decent buck is to become an indecent human being.The film takes us into a kumbha mela of criminality, where we loiter with the pool sharks, their slimy managers, the bouncers and the hit men; not to mention the whores and the chambermaids, the hangers-on and the houseboys, the paid musicians and cabbies, all the field hands who hold the system all together.But still the whole contraption depends on character. It needs a champion. But it is also terrified of champions, because real champions would destroy the system, as Samson tried to do, after he woke up from being captured by it. There is a difference between the character of a hustler, and that of a champion. There is a difference between desire and love. There is a difference between corruption and nobility.The film softly asks us to call our shot: what kind of beings are we? Are we slaves or are we free? Are we fallen human ego constructs? Or are we manifestations of the Almighty?Jayadev.Shunyamurti	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2021/03/hust-1.png	\N	2020-07-10 17:53:38	essay	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.326546	2025-10-28 15:31:24.326546	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
ca22440a-3c6b-442c-8480-712b45731cd7	babaziz-the-prince-who-contemplated-his-soul	Bab’Aziz: The Prince Who Contemplated His Soul	Tonight we have the privilege of visiting the remains of a mythical world that once was real. The title of the film is Bab’Aziz: The Prince Who Contemplated His Soul. Bab’Aziz is the name of the protagonist. The prince is only one of the characters in the stories that he tells and that is intermixed with the story that is unfolding before our three eyes.	text	gyani	0	\N	\N	Tonight we have the privilege of visiting the remains of a mythical world that once was real. The title of the film is Bab’Aziz: The Prince Who Contemplated His Soul. Bab’Aziz is the name of the protagonist. The prince is only one of the characters in the stories that he tells and that is intermixed with the story that is unfolding before our three eyes. If we are non-judgmental (because this film no doubt stinks by Hollywood criteria), we will come to inhabit the strange and barren desert umwelt depicted here, a surreal realm alive with hidden oases and lost kingdoms, the heartbreaking tragicomedy of spiritual illumination, and the awesome beauty of our already finalized marriage with Death. At some point, our third eye pops open with the awakened recognition that we are watching a telling of our own life stories, a cross-section of our psychological development laid out in mythic form. The film is the third segment of a trilogy (I have not seen the others) by a Tunisian auteur who strives to capture the lost taste of the divine madness of the Sufi darveeshes. The Sufis thrived in the Middle Ages. Now they are an oppressed and hunted group considered heretic by Wahhabi strains of Islam. Sufism may be more alive in the West than in the East, though Westerners are still beginners, untrained in the inner craft of transformation. But the great Sufi Shaykhs of the 11th and 12th centuries (by Christian calendar) were the unexcelled alchemists of the spirit, whose accomplishments have altered the morphogenetic field of our planetary reality, and have made accessible to us the salvific wisdom by which our world shall be redeemed. Bab’Aziz is an oriental Decameron or Canterbury Tales. Every character in the film corresponds to an element of consciousness within the Self. We begin our story in the vast desert, right after a sandstorm that has buried our ancient spiritual guide in the flying earth particles of dancing doom among the dunes. He is being dusted off by his traveling partner, his little granddaughter named, of course, Ishtar. She is loyal to him, but admits at the beginning of their odyssey that she nearly left him to return to her pet turtle—a symbol of the threat of psychological regression that always lurks in the shadows, so long as the ego remains at large. Of course, a Sufi guide must be blind to the outer world, in order to see fully in the inner. So the old man can be a proxy for your awakened soul, still dragging around its inner child ego, completing its karmic assignment. The child is afraid of being lost, but our hero calmly tells her that a soul at peace is never lost. Where they are walking is to a gathering of Sufi darveeshes. But our hero does not know where or when this marriage celebration of divinely intoxicated saints betrothed to Ultimate Reality is to take place—nor does anyone else. He only knows that his steps will unerringly take him there, or to whatever station he is assigned along the way. Regardless, he is always already the place where the meeting happens, in the Heart of the Beloved. If you watch this film tenderly, as if your own child made it for you as a gift, there are many gems to be found here. Some are difficult to extract, because they come only as images, like that of the gazelle, without bothering to unpack the many (a thousand and one) Arabian mystery tales starring a gazelle as an adoptive mother, or as the leaping agile soul escaping demonic predators, in perfect harmony with the Real, and yet remaining humble and pure, at one with the Creator. Those who are invited to the vertical dimension will gain many blessings from receiving these archetypal images, even as indistinct messages. It may be noted that our saint is assaulted early on by a man angry at a dervish for stealing the love (and the life) of his brother. It is a case of mistaken identity on one level, but on another it is an accurate charge. He has stolen his own life in order to offer it to God. While he is building a small fire to keep Ishtar warm, she asks Bab’Aziz to tell her a gazelle story. Instead, he tells a tale of the prince who becomes enchanted, not with dancing girls or other sensory pleasures—with those he is disenchanted—but with his own consciousness, with the depths of his Being. Thus, the prince loses interest in the world; he is lost. Or does he begin to be found? Since the prince is also the gazelle, his soul, who is the silent icon that sits at the center of of the saga of the soul, this is also Bab’Aziz in his youth, the beginning phase of his own adult illumination. He exits his exalted social role by chasing a gazelle into the outback. To the others in his kingdom (his kin-dom), he has merely gone mad. His madness shows up as the sudden intrusion of the modern world. Supposedly in the remote sand dunes uncrossable except by camel, the unpleasant engine noise of a motor vehicle is heard, and then a bus roars by on a road not hitherto seen. One would think the contemplation of the soul would lead one backward in time, not forward, and into purer archetypes. But no, one’s karma must be lived out first, on one plane or another. This is the function of kali yuga. Soon we meet the next character, a devotee, in pomo attire as a nomadic backpacker, singing mystical songs of longing for the Beloved. Here is his animus, who will quest until he finds her, his anima-Other, the inner bringer of the bliss of love. His heart is magnetically drawn toward the Fire. As Bab’Aziz says, every soul uses her most precious gift to find her way. For his soul, it was devotional music, the singing of love songs to the Lord, Who responds by sending a messenger in the form of the goddess. Shakti brings one to Shiva, to the Union of the Two Forms of the Absolute, outer and inner. It is a function, not a flaw in the design. But the function can miscarry, if it is not treated with utmost delicacy and divine consideration, based on a mature recognition of the multidimensionality of meanings that pour through the deck of Archetypal cards that make up the ethereal arcana. This felix culpa befalls the next character. I will let the film tell you that story directly, it is already all too well known. Before that, Bab’Aziz is asked if the soul will one day know everything, all of Reality. He ponders. He knows he cannot know if all is known, so long as he is the receiver of Knowledge, and not its Dispenser. This insight leads immediately to the joyous devotional dancing of Ishtar, who begins to remember she is the child goddess. Even old Bab’Aziz starts to dance. The ego is being shed in the bliss of the great adventure that is Life. The child ego asserts itself more and more, and comes quickly to the mastery of survival skills. Individuation is shown by her amicably divided love, between her sage grandfather and her image of the syzygy, the union of anima and animus. But a rupture is inevitable. The same rupture is fractally located at the adult animus level, dividing love between chakra four and chakra two. Thus, one becomes the man who fell into the well. Enough said. His healing requires him to tell the tale to the old man, just like the ancient mariner had to tell his sad tale of albatross abuse as penitence for his mortal sin. In fact this telling, and the listening, the hearing with the third ear, makes him an old man, finally, sitting on the other side of the therapy room. It makes him able to bury his fantasies once and for all. But what he buries first is his paternal superego. Now he is able to live for himself, at last. But what day-job does he take up? He becomes a sand courier, bringing a worthless product to those who have ordered it with ulterior motives. His best customer is the scribe. In other words, the naïve ego brings his sense of unworthiness to his symbolic capacity, and learns to transform his suffering into poetry and philosophy. The scribe opens his creative imagination, all right, but he loses touch with the distinction between dimensions, between celestial metaphors and music, on the one hand, and the temptation to pose as an animal, on the other. The sound track of the Heart opening to love is irresistible. First the sweet-voiced dreams, the butterflies, all the magical adornments—and then the karmic backlash—and the soul falls, dives headlong, into the parallel universe of pain. The loneliness, abandonment, of the outcast scapegoat, savagely ripped apart by passion—but did he not get a foretaste of paradise for his investment? He got as well the obligatory penance time of wandering in the desert that all prophets seem to have to suffer. Interestingly enough, his exodus begins with a vision of the burning bush in the distance, in the barren wasteland, that he is led to believe is the caravan of love in which he will ride with his beloved. Worlds are lost, while other worlds are gained, as we make our choices in life which open doors that close behind us as we go. The rite of passage is never-ending. Not until the final door to God’s innermost chamber opens up before you. As the film makes clear, most go through the desert only looking for the lost object from the past, never facing the Real Other Who is calling us now. Some lucky souls are allowed to travel via the mountains, and some upon the oceans, and they stop to visit only the Painted Desert. In any case, it is time for the child ego to grow up into soulhood and realize her greatness. She recognizes the artwork in the mosque to refer to her divinity. Then she lifts up the veil the pious female to see the mystery of Womanhood, the Archetype of the Feminine, the power of the face, the voice, the energy, the beckoning of both the vertical and horizontal, seeking the integration that can only come from the annihilation of the seeker. The child ascends to the roof, from which vantage point she sees the graceful gazelle waiting in the distance, and now commences her own journey as her adolescent character passes through the barzakh, the psychic barrier, that had separated her from her mature empowerment, and she is absorbed into her Self-given authority to develop fully her magical powers. She does it by getting lost. This seems to be the only way people transform. And of course we grow in the inside first, before we are strong enough to express our truth outwardly as well, and before we even know all that it implies. So Ishtar returns to the nest, but in a fever. Her swoon is guided by her animus lover, who tells the story of his projection of divine love of the anima into manifest form, and Ishtar lives through his dream, and through the waking dream now possessed of that romantic theme. Secretly, she learns the subtle secrets of love. How does the man win the competition, how to sing and sling with such accuracy the arrows of love that the heart of the beloved can be conquered? Not a song of longing and exile, or secret allusions to his unspeakable desire; no, he wins her with a song of ecstasy, with all the atoms of the world on fire with love, of total penetration and permeation by the blissful light of the Supreme Sun, the Light from which we all have come, but the splendor of which had been lost. He lit her up, and the tears of love signaled her consent. And yet it was consent to another exile, another test of faith, passing the test of time. And of course he must also ace the exam of taking care of her black kitten as he trudges ever further into the desert of the Real. The anima absorbs the symbolic phallus of the animus and now she can dress as a man. She will conquer the man’s world and live free of temptation or weakness. They can only meet again as a single voice. But the child imprint remains in superposition with the adult. The fever continues. Child, kitten, and archetypal feminine are in resonance. Thus, the brew of love must ferment, and boil, and integrate all the spices that make up its recipe. It must be consecrated to Allah. Love must be made sacred once again. Love has a task to fulfill. It must become Life itself. All the pairs of opposites must come together. The betrayer and the betrayed must celebrate their supporting acts that coincide as co-egocide. But are we willing to burn in that holy fire, to leave our psychological bones to decompose in the empty wilderness? Now comes the first visit to the cemetery—this one is only the death of projection, of belief in the reality of the world. In dying to the sensory plane of otherness, the sage is able to raise the spirits of the dead, to awaken the djinn. In other words, he is empowered as a Bodhisattva, a Sufi shaykh, a swami siddha, who is granted higher authority by Allah in order to serve at a larger level and historic scope. And then comes the grand finale, separation from life, the reabsorption into Eternity, while yet life goes on as if nothing had happened, because nothing had. New stories are born, in which the old mythologies reappear, world after world. But the moment of death is the gathering up, the kumbha mela of the caliphs of the spirit, who have completed their journey through the Mind of God. And now the celebration starts in earnest. Within magic circles of light, the singing and the dancing, Dionysian yet Apollonian, uninhibited yet solemn satsangs, frenetic yet ecstatic elegies to Allah, Elohim, the Absolute. But the songs are also to Sophia, goddess of the Sufi orders. And the most stirring are entranced surrenderings to the Love that has no name. At this brazen party, avatars emerge, through souls possessed by Krishna, Kalki, Idris, Adam, every Atom dancing with the atmic goddesses and dakinis, and all the prophets beating on their drums and plucking pizzicatos on their heart strings and vocal cords with pranic pulchritude. But no sound can satisfy, except the voice of the Beloved. And even that angelic timbre falls silent at the sight of its reflection. The contemplation of the soul attains apotheosis despite, or because of, the wall that separates, and thus subsumes their particularity into the Universal, the collective illumination of the Night of Time, as God awakens the Earth and collects all souls in preparation for the Dawn about to break upon the world. Our shaykh, Bab’Aziz, lets his hair down one last time, having completed his task and ready for the grave and for the Great Beyond. The gazelle serenely watches over him, as he shuffles off his mortal coil. But not before the Sufi serves his final sermon on the mound of burial. He speaks with compassion to his still fearful identity as carnal creature, terrified of death and the unfathomable infinity of consciousness. The soul lets go of its last tether to the dream, and vanishes into the Mystery. May our own fearful ego vanish likewise as we accompany this Selfic symbol, our Being’s reflection in the water of life, as it dissolves back into the Source, vicariously, through this cinematic Hajj that shouts haji to humanity, re-dreaming heavens heaping with every happiness. Namaste,Shunyamurti\nTopics covered in this teaching:\nEast & WestEastern CultureFilm StudiesMythology	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2020/05/7-1.png	\N	2020-05-20 15:24:37	essay	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.328099	2025-10-28 15:31:24.328099	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
a0c2c03a-9ed0-4e4e-b6a9-5b4c3bfdce47	becoming-nobody-a-film-night-tribute-to-ram-dass	Becoming Nobody: A Tribute To Ram Dass	This collection of precious moments from the talks and interviews of Ram Dass offers a gracious and honest recollection of the spiritual journey he went through publicly, his growth, humor, self-acceptance, and most importantly, his courage in facing death.	text	gyani	0	\N	\N	This collection of precious moments from the talks and interviews of Ram Dass offers a gracious and honest recollection of the spiritual journey he went through publicly, his growth, humor, self-acceptance, and most importantly, his courage in facing death.The film is worth sharing with the sangha because Ram Dass both makes the goal of the quest more clear, and because he enables the listener to more clearly understand that the highest aim is within reach.Ram Dass was a great communicator. He brought a generation along on a ride to chakra four, to the opening of the Heart and the emanation of unconditioned love. Not everyone decided to stay in that frequency, but some made it their new baseline, and from there they caught all the hints thrown out by Ram Dass and free-climbed up the kundalini ladder to chakra seven.His life was an important fractal in the morphogenetic holofield. He produced a new, kinder and gentler archetype of the Jewish-American upper bourgeois intellectual who became a universal human work in progress, demonstrating both the power of the performativity paradox, and the heart-softening grace that comes from surrender to love. Ram Dass became one of the last role models of living spirituality that captured the global imagination. He lived in accord with principles that kept him in the service of Truth. He lived a calling that carried the sense of responsibility to uphold the Dharma, even when his ego failed to rise to the occasion. He made every fall into a learning and then a teaching. He knew how to turn the poison into nectar. And he conveyed the proper way to carry out the great work of Alchemy, always sitting in the sacrificial fire with a smile.It is a joy to say good-bye one more time to our old friend Ram Dass, and perhaps shed a tear and a prayer for his luminous ascension. He has earned the right to apply for graduation. But on the other hand, we’d love him to return.Namaste,Shunyamurti	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2020/02/WEEKLY-TEACHING-YOUTUBE-THUMB-1.jpg	\N	2020-02-15 16:24:59	essay	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.331382	2025-10-28 15:31:24.331382	[]	[]	["IhyQNqkOgPk"]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
1f08001e-f8a6-4153-b9f6-9162f89910fc	the-ghost-of-authenticity-chronicle-of-a-summer	Chronicle of a Summer	The ego is haunted by the shame of its inauthenticity. The ghost of delusion increases its intensity of terror by the ambivalence and self-doubt it shines into its victim with a blinding ray of darkness.\nThe spell-binding film, made in 1961 in France, by Jean Rouch, entitled Chronique d’un Été (Chronicle of a Summer) is such a weapon of egoic destabilization. Rouch had been a cultural anthropologist, studying with the famous Marcel Griaule, whose fame arose from his study of the Dogon tribe in Africa that seemed to know more about the star system Sirius than did modern astronomers—and who claimed their ancestors are from a planet in that system.	text	gyani	0	\N	\N	The ego is haunted by the shame of its inauthenticity. The ghost of delusion increases its intensity of terror by the ambivalence and self-doubt it shines into its victim with a blinding ray of darkness. The spell-binding film, made in 1961 in France, by Jean Rouch, entitled Chronique d’un Été (Chronicle of a Summer) is such a weapon of egoic destabilization. Rouch had been a cultural anthropologist, studying with the famous Marcel Griaule, whose fame arose from his study of the Dogon tribe in Africa that seemed to know more about the star system Sirius than did modern astronomers—and who claimed their ancestors are from a planet in that system. Rouch preferred to study the people of Niger, Ghana, and Cote d’Ivoire, who were then gaining their independence from colonial masters. He was interested in the tensions between rulers and subjects, men and women, workers and bosses, people of different skin color, different political leanings, different levels of investment in the course of human history or in their psychological self-awareness. Then he started to make anthropological film studies of French culture. This film is now a classic. Yet, the movie is often considered both a failure and a breakthrough. Of course such judgments are not to be taken as more than indications of boundaries that Rouch did not dare cross, as well as those he did. He made the film in Paris at a time when many truths were not spoken, were not allowed to be spoken, or were too unbearable to explore, or impossible to explain. Society is an agreement to remain alienated from truths that would explode its hypocrisies and destroy the constructed order. It is a deceptive and deranged disorder masquerading as order, and enforced by thought police who play very rough indeed. But once revealed as fictional, that social order could no longer impose a master’s discourse to force the population to consent to inhumanity exposed to the light of public awareness—at least that is the implicit thesis and motivation of Jean Rouch. He turns his anthropologist’s discerning eye upon the French soul. He puts under his microscope their narcissism, their moral cowardice, their hollow lives of no essence or meaning. We feel the self-loathing, the envy, the fear, the despair and loneliness of every being. The film is shot when the trauma of the recent World War was still agonizing. To face not only the military defeat of France, but its moral defeat, its submission to the Nazi ideology, ate away at their guts like acid. One had to cope with the knowledge of those who flagrantly collaborated with the Nazis, and those who fought in the Resistance or falsely claimed they did. One also had to face the eyes of those French Jews who had been turned in to the government, which sent them to concentration camps in Germany, and who had after the war returned to Paris. One could not deny the tattooed numbers on their arms. But worse, it was the time when the Algerian War was raging. The people of Algeria were fighting for freedom from colonial rule by France. A policy of massacres and torture by the French Armed Forces was underway, and all French people recognized they were accomplices in this terrorism and mass murder. There were many points in the film when it seemed too glib and superficial. One wishes the interviewer would have pushed deeper, demanded more self-revelation, or taken his questions in different directions. But he went as far as he could without his film being banned. There are famous out-takes that showed that Rouch did go much further in certain interviews, but he had to cut them. They were too politically dangerous, or too morally shaming, or just too gut wrenching, and possibly even destabilizing of the audience. He made his point. The film pioneered a movement to be known as cinéma vérité. Rouch’s work formed part of the larger cinematic artistic approach that is remembered as Nouvelle Vague, New Wave. The wave has now receded. And although the filmmakers of today have more special effects to play with, and more leeway of political tolerance—at least in some aspects of life—there is too little interest in truth any longer in the arts. At least, no truth that reveals the falseness of the ego, and the moral imperative of goodness and Self realization, shines through the arts very strongly in these dark days at the end of Kali Yuga. It is important for us to remember the function of art, and for ourselves to become great artists of Truth, whose lives reveal the nobility and courage of the human spirit to overcome its greed, its fear, and its narcissism, and take responsibility for bringing beauty to life and igniting a transformation of our world through the purity of divine love, before it is too late. Who will film a chronicle of our summer in Sat Yoga—and what would such a film reveal about our own willingness to transcend the lies and weaknesses of the ego and fully live in and as the Spirit of Truth? Namaste,Shunyamurti\nTopics covered in this teaching:\nArts & CultureFilm StudiesWestern Culture	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2020/01/8.png	\N	2020-01-14 16:32:58	essay	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.333895	2025-10-28 15:31:24.333895	[]	