50860783-5daa-48f2-9463-c88e45f59567	mozarts-magic-flute-as-directed-by-ingmar-bergman	Mozart’s Magic Flute, As Directed By Bergman	Tonight we shall have the privilege of participating in the operatic magnum opus of Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, completed and staged in 1791, only two years before his death at the age of 35, at the height of his creative powers.	text	gyani	0	\N	\N	Tonight we shall have the privilege of participating in the operatic magnum opus of Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, completed and staged in 1791, only two years before his death at the age of 35, at the height of his creative powers.It is generally considered one of the greatest of all operas. But in technical terms, it was only a singspiel, a shorter more popular form (meaning aimed at the common person as audience) and a mixture of song and dialogue, involving more of a focus on character and plot, and slightly less on the power of sound itself.The libretto for the work was written by Emanuel Schikaneder, the leader of a theatrical troupe that was resident in one of the major opera houses in Vienna at the time. Mozart himself conducted the orchestra and his sister-in-law played one of the lead roles. It was a great popular success from its opening night, and remains so to this day among audiences for opera.However, there is great controversy over why it is so popular or even what it is really about. Many theories can be found, asserting such opinions as that the play is a subversive political commentary on the Empress Maria Theresa, or a conservative call for enlightened absolutism, as it was called, and against the tendencies of republicanism. Modern theorists have attacked it for its racism and anti-feminism. But no consistent case can be made for any such hypotheses. And so, other commentators have simply ridiculed the opera for being a naïve and childish fairy tale aimed at unlettered audiences, a kind of dumbed-down Disney-fication of Western mythology avant la lettre.The more Freudian commentators, of course, see in the magic flute only a phallic symbol, to help him in his Oedipal passage into a higher symbolic manhood, and in the bells given to Papageno a new pair of testicles to help him grow into a more courageous and faithful manhood. But this focus on male psychology is also clearly a very one-sided view and does not fairly evaluate the feminine side of the operatic equation. Jungians likewise offer their archetypal theories, which are no doubt closer to the truth, but still do not give a coherent account of the action.Still others focus on the names of characters, such as Sarastro, the high priest and leader of the secret spiritual brotherhood, and assume that he is modeled on Cagliostro, a contemporary mystic and séance leader. Others say Sarastro refers to Zarathustra, the prophet of the dualistic Zoroastrian religion, which influenced a number of Christian heretical sects, beginning with Manichaeism. But this conflicts with the equally obvious presence of signifiers of ancient Egyptian religion, including references to Isis and Osiris, and the symbol of the pyramid. The music has also been analysed as reflective of numerological Pythagorean symbolic messages, including the employment of the key of E Flat, with its three flat chords to emphasize the Law of Three, which appears in many forms in the unfoldment of the play, and the Law of Seven, which combines, as does the pyramid, both the Three and the Four (as the four elements of Nature), in four triangles that meet at the highest point.All of these theories come up short as complete explanations of the meaning of the drama we are to witness. But what is a documented fact is that Mozart was an active Freemason, was associated with the Illuminati, he was knowledgeable about such esoteric symbolic systems as alchemy, Kabbalah, Renaissance neoplatonic philosophy, ancient Egyptian Hermetic philosophy, and other occult sciences. Mozart was a contemporary of Goethe, another well-read master of the esoteric traditions, who publicly recognized the opera as aimed at initiates, who alone would understand it, and the rest would assume it was a silly patchwork of themes from fairy tales.So how can we best make use of this spectacle as Sat Yogis? I suggest we consider ourselves undergoing our own initiation into a mystery school, into the deepest secrets of the nature of reality. Indeed, culture was initially centered on such mystery-guarding institutions that were responsible for transmitting the knowledge, the maturity, the virtue, and the power of higher consciousness, in short, the capacity for sustaining the Dharma of a healthy community from one generation to the next.Thus, although we can analyze the opera at an exoteric level and find useful if clichéd teachings in it, as are employed somewhat crassly in this version in the form of literal pop-ups of apothegms and aphorisms, and we can also find mesoteric references to teachings of masonic derivation, we can make most use of this great work to view it on the most esoteric level possible.In this paradigm, we can recognize it as expressing nondual reality, from both the perspective of Brahman and that of Atman. All the characters belong to the single consciousness of the Whole. The play shows the Great Chain of Command. But the world, Samsara, has gotten out of order, and now a restoration of Dharma is required. The masculine and feminine principles are at war, the relationship between Nature and Spirit has become inaccurate, and the resistance to growth, transcendence of ego, and sustenance of the power of divine love has become overwhelming. The play shows that all the different esoteric traditions have the same message and the same divine intention. The magic flute is an ancient symbol that goes back to Krishna and beyond. It is also the power of pure speech, transmitting Wisdom that casts a spell of liberation upon the ego and releases the Real Self into full awakening and illumination. The Self returns to rule the manifest world as its own infinite reflection in form of its formless supreme Presence.So in the first scene, we face the initial situation. Man has been overcome by the Beast. The lower chakras have human consciousness on the run. The best of men is unable to fight off the dragon of lust. His masculinity is out of balance. It requires the feminine power of soulful love to control his animalistic sexual drive. But in accepting the help of the feminine principle, he also comes under the influence of the female fury at the male principle that has allowed the situation to become so oppressive and dictatorial, so objectifying and defiling of the goddess. The feminine projection of anti-male anger must also be balanced. Thus, the symbolic guides on the initiatory journey are three young boys, who remain innocent but fully male in their attitudes and influence.The Shadow is represented by Monostatos (One-Dimensional Man), who wants to sexually defile Pamina, but who is held back, just barely, by the Law. Papageno is the male ego in its more socialized form, but it remains infantile and unable to go through a full transformation. The ego is only capable of supporting the sexual relationship at a level that can parent children, but cannot function as a spiritual guide for society. It remains narcissistic, even though loyal to the higher guidance in its way.But Tamino symbolizes the Buddhi, who goes through the various ordeals of celibacy, of self-restraint, of silence, in order to attain an inner unification of the divine masculine with the divine feminine at the level of pure Spirit. The purification of the consciousness leads once more to the renewal of the world. The old order of ego, of anger, projection, and conflict between the man and the woman is overcome dialectically, and the unification of Nature, Reason, and Wisdom becomes manifest. The conditions of a new Sat Yuga have been attained, and the transmission of power can now ensue. This is the coronation of the new king and queen, and the abdication of Sarastro, having completed his own charitra, his own divine act of deliverance. May we all undergo the catharsis of this inner transformation as we participate mystically in this great work of inspired art.	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2019/07/10.png	\N	2019-07-03 16:53:46	essay	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.335495	2025-10-28 15:31:24.335495	[]	[]	["ZB7Ytw7HwMM"]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
cac697cd-1b83-4d25-96e9-4ab2884e4e60	states-phases-levels-and-types-of-consciousness-a-new-model-of-psychoactivity	A New Model of Psychoactivity	In the traditional framework, there are four states of consciousness—waking (jagrat), dreaming (swapna), deep sleep (sushupti), and Samadhi (referred to in this model as turiya, which means fourth). When the yogi attains permanent Samadhi (usually referred to as sahaja nirvikalpa Samadhi) then this becomes the only state, which subsumes all the rest—and this ultimate state is referred to as “beyond the fourth” or turiyatita.	text	gyani	0	\N	\N	In the traditional framework, there are four states of consciousness—waking (jagrat), dreaming (swapna), deep sleep (sushupti), and Samadhi (referred to in this model as turiya, which means fourth). When the yogi attains permanent Samadhi (usually referred to as sahaja nirvikalpa Samadhi) then this becomes the only state, which subsumes all the rest—and this ultimate state is referred to as “beyond the fourth” or turiyatita.Clearly, this model is insufficient for an accurate understanding of the nature, permutations, and trajectory of evolution of personal into transpersonal and finally liberated consciousness. It is offered only as an interesting museum piece helping us to understand consciousness in a simple way that can be communicated to a naïve beginner. The real picture is much more complex. It may be useful to attempt to formulate an alternative model.Let us refer to phases as unfoldments on the same level of consciousness, the levels referring to ego, soul, and atman, or Self. States would refer to discontinuous appearances and irruptions of phenomena from different levels, coming as intrusions into and disruptions of a normal mode of psychic unfoldment. (We could also add registers of consciousness into the model—the knotted intersections of imaginary, symbolic, and real that constitute the ego and the soul levels of consciousness. But we will leave them out of this analysis for reasons of simplification.)Sat Yoga postulates the following:From the biological perspective, we can say that indeed there are three ordinary phases of consciousness for the human organism that alternate as a function of the optimal circadian rhythm supporting the vital processes of the individual.But when we approach these three phases from a psychological perspective, we discover that there are many variations and sub-phases within each phase, plus interruptions in the form of mostly pathological states, in addition to the transitional phases that may or may not function optimally.So, for example, one may attempt to transition normally from deep sleep to wakefulness—this transitional phase has been called by Jungians the hypnopompic phase—but discover that one is stuck in an in-between state that is referred to as sleep paralysis. But one is obviously not asleep in the usual sense in this state. One is quasi-awake but not able to operate the body. The body does not respond to the conscious will of the mind. The body remains asleep while the mind is awake. The mind then becomes alarmed at its condition, and enters a fear state until the gears of the body mesh again and the organism awakens and becomes once more in sync with the mind’s intentions and its normal, though illusory, feeling of being at-one with the body.Sleep paralysis has similarities to the coma condition, except that it is transitory, while a coma can last for years or become terminal. Clearly the coma, and its short-term relative sleep paralysis, demonstrate that consciousness has only an occasional relationship to the physical organism, and that consciousness can enter into non-physical conditions in which it cannot return to the body by its own will.The transitional phase between waking and falling asleep—called the hypnogogic phase—can also be problematic, producing hallucinatory fears, repetitive affect-stimulating thoughts, fantasies, and paranoid anxieties of loss of control, and lead to insomnia and other chronic sleep disturbances.A variety of different sub-phases and abnormal states can occur within the sleep phase, including sleepwalking and night terrors, and other malignant forms of what is called parasomnia.Consciousness can also lead a separate life from that of the organism, as shown in such events as a near death experience, in which the consciousness not only separates from the body, and enters other, higher dimensions of reality, but returns with detailed memories of having gone to those other dimensions, where usually great wisdom and power were available and bestowed, and one retains afterward the new knowledge of the spiritual nature of reality and the higher laws of living that determine our destiny. The event will usually entail a palpable change in the attitude and character of the returnee, and often produces a miraculous healing of the returnee’s physical organism.There is also a psychological capacity that operates in an altered state of awareness called remote viewing—in which the person can sense or intuit locations extremely distant from the body, and sometimes events that are happening at those locations.There is also the well-known out-of-body experience, in which consciousness not only intuits what is happening at a distance, but actually experiences the reality of leaving the body and traveling in space in real time and being able to overhear conversations in distant places and perceive what is happening with the senses of sight and hearing fully functioning in the bodiless condition. One can train to achieve a full mastery of both remote viewing and the ability to engage in out-of-body movement in space so that one can do so at will without limitation, which is referred to as astral traveling.There are also reported experiences of time travel. And as with remote viewing, there is the more common phenomenon of receiving a vision of a future event, or sometimes just a premonition. This capacity can also be cultivated, which can lead to the ability to prophesy, or predict the future. A minor variant of this is the déjà vu, in which one has the sense of having already gone through an experience previously.There are many other permutations that occur in the waking phase of consciousness, leading to what are generally called altered states of consciousness, including those induced by the ingestion of psychoactive chemicals. Altered states can also be induced by hypnosis and other forms of trancework, rites and rituals, some including physical ordeals, some involving drumming or other kinds of music and dance, or heightened sexual arousal, and longer term and more gradual alterations of consciousness, such as that produced by long fasting, or by entering into radically different environmental conditions, as in deep diving or spacewalking as an astronaut.All the above phenomena relate to the ego and its illusory sense of being in a world that pre-exists its arrival. Beyond all this is the more subtle reality of the soul, which recognizes all that arises and changes to be its own dream, aspects of its nature viewed in projected form, being re-collected through understanding and acceptance into aboriginal unity.The kundalini yogi, functioning at the soul level, recognizes each of the seven chakras as signifying a different vibrational vortex that can suck consciousness into an egoless state ruled by the affect that is expressed in that frequency, and can enter into non-ordinary states that produce powerful effects on the body and its behavior, not all of which are positive.A chakra one vortex can lead to demonic realms, hallucinatory horrors of dismemberment and other torment, autism, psychosis, or even suicide.The chakra two vortex can lead to hypersexual acting out, nymphomania, fatal attractions, lustful thoughts that lead to porn addiction, compulsive masturbation, and obsessive focus on the sexual body parts of others or one’s own body.The chakra three vortex leads to one going berserk, in murderous rage, blind fury, and uncontrolled destructiveness.The chakra four vortex produces sublime feelings of divine love without an object.The chakra five vortex leads into a labyrinth of understanding and wisdom, symbolic insight into ever more subtle levels of truth.The vortex of chakra six manifests as light and power, the command of the elements, paranormal psychic capacities, full mastery of the brain and body’s potentialities.The chakra seven vortex is the portal to total liberation, absorption into the Supreme Real.What a traditionally-oriented advaita yogi is interested in is chakra seven, expanding consciousness beyond the limits of the ego, not through a projection of the ego into outer space, nor by the ego’s entering into temporary altered states through taking psychedelic substances or engaging in other kinds of trance induction, but by a total and permanent dissolution of the ego identity and its frame of reference—and timeless perfect realization of the Absolute.This leads to a hyper-dimensional shift of consciousness into an omnicentric egoless awareness of the entire apperceptual field and the boundless luminous intelligent void in which all of reality is contained and pervaded as a single whole, a unified manifestation of the Self. This state of aware presence is timeless, blissful, intuitively knowledge-filled, but in an implicate order that is the ground of Being, knowing in a thought-free manner in which knower and known are one.This is the final phase of the destiny of consciousness, recognized as a moebius strip in which samsara and nirvana seem to alternate, but are really the same, omnipresent and empty, without qualities, the Nirgun Para Brahman, yet also filled to overflowing with luminous love, joy and delight, the blissful Vaikuntha of Vishnu, a great work of infinite artistry and indescribable beauty, the nameless Tao, eternal yet evanescent and illusory, a perfect thought wave in the oceanic Buddha-nature mind of God: the Self.Namaste,Shunyamurti\nTopics covered in this teaching:\nPhilosophyYoga	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2020/05/1-2.jpg	\N	2019-07-02 17:33:43	essay	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.337694	2025-10-28 15:31:24.337694	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
8d5aefe7-a50c-4936-b9d5-04586f29d9c7	sat-yoga-meditation	Sat Yoga Meditation	It is now widely recognized in the fields of medicine and psychology that meditation is a powerful instrument for the management of stress, the strengthening of the immune system, and for the acceleration of healing processes in the body. Many clinical studies have validated the effectiveness of meditation not only for physical healing and the diminution of anxiety, but for the improvement of the quality of life. The sense of happiness and inner contentment has been correlated to the capacity to meditate and sustain states of serenity and stillness. But for the Sat Yogi, meditation implies a great deal more than that.	text	gyani	0	\N	\N	It is now widely recognized in the fields of medicine and psychology that meditation is a powerful instrument for the management of stress, the strengthening of the immune system, and for the acceleration of healing processes in the body. Many clinical studies have validated the effectiveness of meditation not only for physical healing and the diminution of anxiety, but for the improvement of the quality of life. The sense of happiness and inner contentment has been correlated to the capacity to meditate and sustain states of serenity and stillness. But for the Sat Yogi, meditation implies a great deal more than that.Meditation is the transcendence of the ego. Through silencing the mind, that is, through stopping the production of thought-constructs, the awareness is able to enter higher states of Being. Awareness comes to realize itself as unbounded, formless, timeless freedom. The original and ultimate state of the Self is indescribable. The closest one can come to portraying the feeling nature of our essence is to use such terms as love, wonderment, joy, power, crystalline clarity, absolute emptiness, radiant presence, infinite intelligence, complete unity with all that is, and utter endless rapturous bliss.This transcendence is the final attainment of Sat Yoga. But for most people, meditation is very difficult in the beginning, and there is a long learning curve. This is because the ego-mind resists the state of inner silence. The ego is threatened by silence. To maintain its supremacy over the awareness, it must constantly weave its narrative thread, throwing out images of the past, replaying scenes and words with an emotional charge, fomenting anger, the desire for vengeance, or leaking out feelings of shame, guilt, or inadequacy. The ego-mind is itself captured by a censoring agency and programmed by unconscious phantasies that serve as templates in which experience is interpreted. Other possibilities are locked out. The ego-mind holds consciousness trapped in the box of its preconceptions.When one first attempts to meditate, the ego-mind either will not desist from constant chatter, or else it will put one to sleep. It will try its best to convince one that meditation is boring, a hopeless waste of time. It may create diversions like itches, coughs, muscular discomfort, or distraction by outside noises. The most banal ideas will come into the mind, anything to take one away from the present moment. Meditation is for most people a difficult struggle, at least in the beginning stages.A number of methods have been developed over the centuries to help calm and center the mind to prepare it for deep meditation. This is the real importance of doing asanas, for example. These hatha yoga exercises can slow down the metabolism and de-stress the body, to create an altered state of consciousness in which one can enter into transcendent levels more easily. But simply taking a few minutes at the start of a sitting meditation session to breathe deeply and relax the muscles will accomplish much the same result. Eventually, a simple affirmation that one’s body is relaxing will do the trick.Breathing exercises, called pranayamas, can also be useful. The functioning of the mind is linked to the rhythm of respiration. By slowing down the breathing, the mind can be slowed down as well. But again, all this can be accomplished through simply centering the attention in the awareness that precedes the I-thought. Remaining as the silent witness of the body/mind will slow down the breathing and metabolism naturally and effortlessly.Meditative music can also be used. Soft, slow, graceful music can soothe the mind and entrain the attention into a light state of trance. But soon one loses focus on the outer music, no matter how beautiful it may be, and enters into the realm of inner silence and beatitude, where time seems to stop. Once this realm has been touched, and the Presence of God has been felt, then one can simply remember this exalted state in order to return to it in future meditations.Guided meditation can also be helpful in the beginning, following the voice of a guide into gradually more profound inner states. Eventually, of course, one wants to be independent of outside assistance. In the interim, prayer is a useful way of focusing, bringing one’s attention and intention together on the presence of God within. Mantras, or the repetition of sacred words that point to one’s identity with the Supreme Self, can also be used. For those who do not have a religious attitude in the beginning, counting breaths can be an effective technique. Ultimately, it is the repeated application of will, through any means, impelled by the purpose of making the mind obey the higher intelligence, that brings consciousness into a stable peaceful silence. Now meditation can really begin. If there is an authentic attitude of devotion, the process will of course be accelerated.The most direct ways of entering into deeper states of presence in meditation are known as Self-inquiry and Self-affirmation.Self-inquiry consists of asking (in thought, at first, but in advanced stages without verbal thought) the question “who am I?” and then silently apperceiving the answer. This method was taught by the great modern sage Ramana Maharshi. The question “who am I” is not asked in order to elicit a discourse on one’s identity. It is not intended to evoke images of oneself as an entity in the world. Rather, the question is asked in order to bring one into a state of complete formless subjectivity. The question could even be phrased “what is the I?” to more clearly establish the non-personal basis of I-ness. Or, What does it mean to be an “I”? This is of course a profound philosophical question. But it is not meant to stimulate philosophical conceptualizations. Rather, the question is asked to oneself in thought precisely to bring one’s attention to the inner presence that precedes philosophical speculation. The inner presence of I transcends language and identity. The real I is indescribable. To know the I, I can only be the I.The inner inquiry is therefore intended to bring conscious awareness back to its source in the primal wordless and formless Presence. During meditation, whenever the mind goes off on some tangent, the observing intelligence should stop that wandering tendency by asking “whose thoughts are these?” and recognizing that they must belong to the I. Then, attention can return to the question “who am I,” and thence to the state of silent Presence. By consistently bringing back the mind from its wanderings, it will eventually learn not to wander, but like a trained dog, to heel and to obey the real I. Gradually there will be less and less need to ask the questions, and more time can be spent in silent Presence. Eventually, the imaginary I of the ego, as well as the​ ​conceptual I that monitors it, will disappear altogether, and the boundless, luminous, blissful emptiness of the infinite Self will be constantly, timelessly, here and now.The method of Self-affirmation can achieve the same end. Instead of asking a question, however, which can stimulate in intellectual personalities a flow of ideas, one simply affirms the highest understanding at the outset. Thus, when one sits to meditate, one simply thinks an affirmation such as “I am the Supreme Reality.” Or “I am the One Self.” Or such variations as “I am He,” or “I am That.” Or “God and I are one.” Or simply “I am silent Presence.” Or even more simply: “I AM.” Then one stops the thought process and enters fully into the state of pure awareness. If the mind starts pulling one away from the silence, simply re-affirm the original affirmation and return to pure Divine Presence.If one is more comfortable with a dualist paradigm of relationship to the Supreme Being, then that can also be affirmed with a heartfelt statement such as “I belong to You alone, oh God,” or “I melt in the oneness of love with You.”One can also choose a particular divine attribute to focus on, such as “I am the Self of pure Love.” Or: “I am the Blissful Self.” Or: “I am the Peaceful Self.”The affirmations are not an end in themselves, but an entry-point for merging into the Silence that transcends identity. The only danger in using these methods is that the ego will later misappropriate to itself the qualities or status of the Supreme Self. One must always keep in mind that the ego is a fiction. The Self is not the bodily entity with which the ego identifies, but the transpersonal awareness that is one with all that is. The Self is all and yet also absolute nothingness.Namaste,Shunyamurti\nTopics covered in this teaching:\nMeditation	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2020/05/1-2.jpg	\N	2019-07-01 20:12:52	essay	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.341153	2025-10-28 15:31:24.341153	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
736df39a-a786-4f12-83f6-a054de2547a6	meditation-the-joy-of-transcendence	Meditation: The Joy of Transcendence	Meditation is the core activity of ancient Yoga as well as nearly every other spiritual and religious tradition. In Christianity, it is called contemplative prayer. It is now used in secular contexts as well by people simply seeking inner peace and relief from stress. Science has proven its effectiveness.	text	gyani	0	\N	\N	Meditation is the core activity of ancient Yoga as well as nearly every other spiritual and religious tradition. In Christianity, it is called contemplative prayer. It is now used in secular contexts as well by people simply seeking inner peace and relief from stress. Science has proven its effectiveness.Meditation is the art of developing the full potentials of our consciousness. The fundamental principle is to slow down, and eventually halt, the flow of thoughts in the mind. The more silent and still is the inner space of our consciousness, the more serene, happy, and empowered we will feel.This taming of the mind, which for most people is wild and uncontrollable, results in an extraordinary level of self-mastery. Once the mental focus has been trained to respond to our will, we can turn our attention into a laser beam of pure concentration, and achieve much higher levels of skill and effectiveness in any activity we do.We can read faster and retain more information. We can improve our performance in every field, from business to sports to music to creative writing to critical thinking. This is because a quiet mind is more receptive to inspiration and innovative ideas.A meditative mind is more flexible, clear, and unbiased, thus more capable of making accurate decisions and changing directions when called for. A calm mind tends to be more open and loving, more able to listen deeply to others, and less egocentric.In a meditative state, one is more likely to heal quickly from any illnesses, since the immune system is strengthened by the relaxed, even flow of life energy through the organism. This vital power in Yoga is called prana. In Chinese, the word is chi. Increasing the flow of chi is the basis of traditional Chinese medicine and all the Eastern martial arts. An advanced meditator can even direct the flow of spiritual energy to others to augment their healing and sense of wellbeing.Meditation is used by spiritually-oriented seekers to attain what has variously been called Self-realization, God-realization, enlightenment, Buddha Mind, Emptiness, the Tao, or by endless other such exalted terms.This level of meditation is reached when the mind has learned to abide constantly in inner silence in the heart, or the core of our Being. It brings about transcendence of the ego. With that come wisdom, courage, universal love, and a lasting sense of sublime oneness with Ultimate Reality.Many advanced meditators also attest that this highest level of contemplation results in paranormal capacities, including telepathy, accurate premonitions of future events—sometimes called prophecy—and astral travel, or the ability of consciousness to journey safely out of the body to distant locations and higher dimensions. Some say it also enables subtle perception of angels, divine radiance, and other kinds of visions well known to mystics.To get started meditating, there are many easy techniques for beginners. One way, used in Zen monasteries and other such centers of meditation, involves the counting of breaths.One should begin by finding a quiet space where one will not be interrupted and sit comfortably—no difficult Yoga poses are necessary—with the back straight (not hunched over or with the torso twisted), take a few initial deep breaths to release any excess tension, and close one’s eyes to tune out visual distractions. Calming music can be playing in the background, if you wish.Then, begin to count each in-breath and out-breath. As you breathe in, think “one.” Then, as you breathe out, think “two.” Count up to ten and then start again at “one.” That is all. Keep this up for as many rounds as you wish. You will soon notice that your breathing becomes slower and more regular, and with that your metabolism will slow down, the body will spontaneously relax, and there will be a lovely feeling of peacefulness and refreshment.If you were to hook up your head with electrodes, as is often done in laboratory tests of meditation, you would discover that your brainwaves gradually shift from beta to alpha waves, and then, if you continue long enough, into even deeper theta and delta states. These shifts have been shown to produce many positive, lasting effects on our health and personality development into more integrated wholeness.Another popular method, for non-religious meditators, is to simply repeat a syllable or word that represents calming and relaxation to you, or even one that is meaningless, without the counting of breaths. This will have the same effects as the first technique. Of course, religious people will prefer to repeat a Name of God, a short prayer, or a mantra that has deep meaning to them and brings a sense of greater closeness with God or with whatever we conceive of as our Supreme Beingness.There are also techniques that involve keeping the eyes open, including staring at a candle flame, a mandala, a beautiful work of visual art, or a religious icon.Advanced meditators often prefer a method called Self-enquiry. In this approach, you simply ask yourself the question, “Who am I?” Then, rather than answering the question with words, ideas or images, you search within for the center of your Being—beyond all superficial levels of identity, such as your profession or religion or gender orientation or age—and let your attention focus ever more deeply in your innermost sense of Selfhood.This can lead to what feels like a floating, timeless state of bodiless, eternal presence, an infinite expanse of luminous and joyous energy, a sense of liberation from all worries and of profound goodness, security, and confidence that all is perfect. You will know that you are supported in your existence and empowered to live in happiness—in short, what in religious terms, would be called a state of grace.One popular aspect of meditation that attracts newcomers is what has come to be called mindfulness (or vipassana, a Theravada Buddhist term). This is the process of noticing all that arises in consciousness, without reacting to it, without judging it, without identifying with it, and—most importantly—without allowing any stream of thoughts connected with it to divert one from silent presence.This would include reacting to every itch and kink in the body, as well as to thoughts tinged with some emotion, or some extraneous task one must perform later that day, or other ideas, images, and memories that interfere with the steadiness of attention. By not reacting, all such arisings will soon disappear and inner peace will be re-established. It is important not to attack oneself for losing one’s center, as that will start a vicious cycle of negative thinking. Simply wait patiently and witness all that appears and the mind will free itself from its habitual self-deceptions.People considering taking up the practice of meditation often ask if it is better to sit home alone to do it, or more effective in a group setting. The answer is that a group that is led by an advanced meditator (and the more advanced the better, to be able to deal appropriately with spiritual crises that can indeed come up in this practice) and that offers a philosophy congenial to one’s own, and not demanding of blind belief in some creed, will accelerate one’s progress, for several reasons.One is that, as just indicated, once engaged seriously in this practice, many questions will arise because of various strange mental and physical phenomena that can arise in the course of what amounts to a stirring up of the unconscious levels of the psyche through one’s sustained concentration. For the most part, this is a hygienic release of repressed Shadow material from childhood (to use Carl Jung’s term), which in religious terminology would be called the purification of the soul.It is because of the fact that our subjectivity is split into conscious, repressed, and superconscious sectors that there is both the desire to meditate—to gain true wholeness and self-understanding and mastery—and there is the inevitable arising of obstacles and moments of critical encounter with forbidden and unbearable truths. This is why it is imperative to have an ethical, highly experienced, and knowledgeable teacher if one wants to pursue this avenue of growth beyond superficial levels. It is not all hearts and flowers, but also dealing with thorns and dark nights of the soul.To gain skill in this inner work of self-purification, other meditative approaches will eventually be required in addition to mere mindfulness. These include the capacity for analytic meditation and gyana yoga. The analytic skill covers the same ground as psychoanalysis—that of understanding repressed desires, fears, confusions, guilt feelings, and inhibitions—but does so from a simpler, more real and more spiritual paradigm of our true nature and our power to let go of the past.This kind of ethical self-knowledge is necessary to claim the authentic self-mastery and authority over the contents of one’s own mind to be able to deconstruct any disempowering or self-sabotaging thoughts that come from the lower unconscious sectors of our psyche (which is a lot more vast and multidimensional than most of us trained in a rational, scientific paradigm imagine).On the other hand, the gyana yoga—based on accurate knowledge of the superconscious levels of our Being, is useful in navigating the advanced stages of meditation that open up to the higher Mind—enabling us to understand and make use of the visions and insights and sublime feelings that will be received in deep Samadhi (the very advanced absorption in the innermost core of consciousness that produces the ecstatic energies and wisdom that many seekers yearn for).Another reason to choose to meditate in a group or esoteric school setting with an adept teacher (a setting that is known in Yoga as a satsang—a gathering of those seeking the inmost Truth of our Being) is that during meditation people emanate an energy field, and a group energy field is more powerful than an individual one. So just by sitting in a positive and peaceful energy field created by a number of meditators together in a room can set up a resonance effect in one’s own inner space (since all our minds are in quantum entanglement, as science has discovered) and boost one’s own vibrational energy levels enormously, to get one past the breakers of initial resistance, until one is swimming in the deep cool waters of a sea of serenity.There are many places one can go to study and practice meditation (and of course one should make a careful and informed choice before making a commitment, since there are many charlatans and cult groups that have ulterior motives), and many books written on the subject. But the main thing is just to start doing it, and make it a regular habit—even if for only a half-hour a day. Make sure you do not go to sleep during your practice or waste your time chattering to yourself, but stay on course with your chosen technique. Soon, almost without recognizing the change, your life will take a turn for the better.People will tell you that you look younger and more energized. Some will ask if you just came back from a vacation. Others will notice a glow of wellbeing in your aura. Old unwanted habits will fall away by themselves, anxieties will disappear, and a positive attitude of being successful and prosperous will stay constant and actually bring new opportunities and successes into your life.In the challenging and stressful times we are now living in, the ability to meditate is an essential tool in helping us get the most out of life. It will keep us calm and cool when under pressure, it will give us the fearlessness to face down intimidation, and the discernment not to be taken in by the false promises or seductions of others or our own wishful projections.Skill in meditation will, in short, make us wiser, without having to go through being sadder first. It will make us more realistic, with more acute “street smarts”—but we will also recognize that we live in an unlimited reality with such extraordinary potentials that those ignorant of the insights and powers gained in meditation will foolishly call them mere fantasies. Meditation is a direct path to levels of individuation and Self-discovery undreamt of by most people, and unfortunately still repressed by most of our society.Soon, if you discipline yourself from the beginning to practice even when you would rather watch TV or surf the internet, meditation will have become second nature and you will find yourself naturally meditating whenever you have a short break in the day, and that even these little dips into inner peace enrich your life more than you can express in words.Namaste,Shunyamurti\nTopics covered in this teaching:\nMeditation	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2020/05/1-2.jpg	\N	2019-07-01 20:12:16	essay	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:24.343171	2025-10-28 15:31:24.343171	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
966a516f-035b-4191-bb62-554c73b9d35e	knowledge-removes-suffering	Accurate Knowledge Removes All Fear and Suffering	Once it is recognized that the apparent world is only the mind engaged in dreaming, then the nonduality of consciousness and its contents can be understood and its vast implications can be unfolded. But it can take some time to digest and integrate all the binaries (the polarities, like good and evil, immanent and transcendent) in order to gain accurate knowledge that brings freedom from suffering—even the awareness that there is no suffering, since the world and the whole seeming multiplicity of sentient inhabitants are unreal. The sticking point is the resistance to recognizing that you, as a being in the world, are also unreal. The delusional mental apparatus must be terminated.	videoandaudio	gyani	0	\N	\N	\N	https://www.members.satyoga.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2025/02/3Fri-Feb-21_Members-Teaching_220917_Avadhuta-Revolution_Midday-GM-Teaching-QA.png	4715	2025-02-21 12:36:44	qa	\N	0	2025-10-28 15:31:23.975826	2025-11-04 11:15:46.425793	["be3146a004cdb24b908134aa2ea40493"]	["zr5mu-17f563f-pb"]	[]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	[]
